The course introduces the structure of paleontology as a science, the problems of life, an overview of marine and terrestrial habitats and the main fossil groups in the form of a systematic overview, together with a practical part on the use of fossils for geological purposes.Objectives/eesmärkid:  Developing of knowledge on the main fossil groups, marine and terrestrial habitats, evolution, paleoecology, biostratigraphy and the analysis of paleontological data.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The graduate of the course ... * has knowledge on the anatomy, distribution and practical geological application of the main fossil groups in the correlation of rocks of different ages on necessary level for a professional geologist; * is able to distinguish the main groups of stratigraphically important fossils and has general knowledge of the basics of classification of the most important groups; * is able to assess the evolutionary and geological significance of collected fossils; * knows the general principles of stratigraphic use of fossils; * has the necessary level of professional knowledge of biostratigraphy and biostratigraphic units; * has sufficient knowledge about paleontological sampling, laboratory preparation methods and special paleontological software; * is able to apply the above knowledge and the basic methods of paleontological data analysis in practice.
